Data analysis

fse

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict fse with age, group and time_point (formula: fse ~ 1 + age + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The models total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.74) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.18. The models intercept, corresponding to age = 0, group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 14.47 (S.E. = 2.77, p < .001, 95% CI [9.04, 19.89]). Within this model:

  • The effect of age is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.08, S.E. = 0.05, p = 0.093, 95% CI [-0.01, 0.17]; Std. beta = 0.30, 95% CI [-0.05, 0.66])
  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.81, S.E. = 1.37, p = 0.554, 95% CI [-3.50, 1.88]; Std. beta = -0.23, 95% CI [-0.99, 0.53])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.09, S.E. = 0.89, p = 0.919, 95% CI [-1.65, 1.83]; Std. beta = 0.03, 95% CI [-0.46, 0.52])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and positive (beta = 3.30, S.E. = 1.29, p = 0.010, 95% CI [0.77, 5.82]; Std. beta = 0.93, 95% CI [0.22, 1.64])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
